author: Chris
text: XCITERO how so?  How does financial success equate to quality in any way?  Are you a huge Bieber fan too?  Got all the One Direction albums?  I love AF; I own all of their stuff on CD, including this which I foolishly pre-ordered.  I couldn‚Äôt have been more disappointed with this album though.  Outside of a couple of tracks it‚Äôs garbage.

author: XCITERO
text: This evolution was foreshadowed in The Suburbs; Sprawl II is the best Everything Now song, that's not on the album. Face it, Reflektor and EN will be the albums most fondly remembered 30/40 years down the line. Not Funeral.

author: Chris
text: XCITERO As much as I love Funeral and most of Neon Bible, The Suburbs is easily my favorite AF album.  I admit Reflektor wasn‚Äôt my favorite but I still think it‚Äôs an extremely good album.  EN is just a huge misstep though and actively obnoxious much of the time.  I strongly disagree it‚Äôll be held up as a superior work in future.

text: At 1:26 the screen goes completely black, except for a blue eye with five lines on each side. Anyone out there know if this symbol has any significance?

author: Stealth Emerald
text: Here is a start > spiritually, celestial blue represents heaven, and the healing power of God, truth and vision. The eye also represents 'Eye of Providence', the 3rd eye/inner eye/single eye. (although some twist it as the evil eye and misinterpret the All Seeing Eye...LoL). It's the omnipresent eye of the creator peering into our soul, the window of the soul is also the eyes, always to do with spirit though. Whereas in many ancient cultures the blue eye was also used as protection to ward off the evil eye. The Gods Vishnu/Krishna/Shiva are blue (as with many Hindu Gods...referring to their blue aura or blue blood, blue Gods) , in egypt Amon was depicted as blue, hebrew priests wore blue and the bible has many mentions of blue in reference with God > it's why the Israeli flag is blue and white. Folklore mentions Druids wearing blue, the Maya painted their sacrifices blue in hopes for rain, the Chinese have their blue dragon etc, etc. \nFive mostly represents the elements > earth, air/wind, water, fire and spirit. Since we are electric, resonance frequency is being represented thru the 5 lines...'we' are sound waves (musical math, harmonics) manifest in this onesong/universe;) The throat (5th) chakra is blue (communication, expression & connection), while the third eye is indigo (which is still royal blue but leading into deep violet). So with auras > if one has achieved the highest form of pure perfection it is white but if one chooses to remain in action and of service to the all, it will be electric blue. Our energy can transmute/transform/transcend from lower to higher vibrations thru the blue light, sometimes seen in mediation, some also refer to it as the blue ray....but truly it all ends up with the same mystical meaning..LoL. Spiritual awakening...hey some would even call it the healing start towards enlightenment, illumination, divinity or finding God. \nBut ultimately....the only significance it has for you is the one you intuitively feel, the one you give it or what you make of it:) Everything is one and now....LoL. Peace Scot

author: Subparanon
text: A.F. Please please please consider your main stay style, and what your fans expect from an  A.F. album and whether different styles of music really fit under t hat umbrella, or whether they should be done under side projects. I mean U2 for example has their sound, but when they wanted to do different kinds of music, they created The Passengers, and U2 fans still ate it up, but Passengers was not a U2 sound, so they didn't incorporate it under the U2 name. I know it's so easy for people to shit on something you feel passionate about and it takes 2 seconds to say you don't like something, and months to actually create something and it's unfair, but honest feedback is important to consider. I'm not feeling this album and I'm a long time lover of your albums.

author: rjonesbeau1
text: Subparanon Plenty of bands and artists have dramatically changed style with a huge uproar. This has included many of AF's influences such as The Cure, David Bowie and  Joy Division/New Order. After an album or so those changes were accepted and often preferred to their original style so I don't see why Arcade Fire can't try it either. The only new song i'm not at all fussed by is 'Sign of Life'. This song is just a more chilled, less bitter version of Sprawl ii.

author: Vinay Pateel
text:
So the past couple of weeks were kinda dull. I was going about my life, working and eating and showering and generally trying to have fun. But it seemed like the spark of my life was kinda blurred. Something seemed missing.
And then Arcade Fire, Galantis, Foster The People - all of em released music one after the other bam bam bam!
And everything in life seems so much better now! Its like increasing the saturation of colour in my life. I LOVE my showers now while all this music is playing on repeat!
.
.
This is how drug addicts probably feel.
Now I have more empathy towards them.

Had this been their first album, it may also have been their last. \n\nEvolution in a band is a great thing. Radiohead's Kid A being the prime example. This is more a mis-step, however. I'd love for them to continue down this road, musically, but they need to be more aware, creatively, of what they're good at. author: Mylo the Zoo-loving Scientist
text:
I honestly don't think people who have issues with this album dislike it simply because Arcade Fire changed their sound. I think the problem is they can't articulate the true reason why they dislike it, so they use that argument instead. The truth is, every album of theirs has sounded different. Neon Bible didn't sound like Funeral, The Suburbs didn't sound like Neon Bible, and Reflektor didn't sound like The Suburbs. But everyone loved those albums for the most part. 

Everything Now is my least favorite Arcade Fire album.  I only really like a handful of songs on it (this one, "Everything Now" primarily), but it's not because the album just sounds different. "Creature Comfort" and "Signs of Life," for example, have awesome instrumentation that I really enjoyed, but the vocal melodies and the lyrics of both were really off-putting to me personally. I feel like Arcade Fire put out a half-baked record. I liked the new sound and the ideas behind the album, but felt they came up short with their execution.

I obviously can't speak for everybody, but I just don't think you can write someone off as "not a fan" when they dislike something new. I absolutely love Arcade Fire, but I'm not down with about 60% of this album. It doesn't mean I wouldn't go see them in concert and have the time of my life. Like another user said, what is crap music, as well as what is awesome music, is all subjective, and people have every right to explain why they feel the way they do.

author: Porsalin Live
text: It's not about the capability to change. It's about what you're gravitated towards and what naturally jives with what you like. I can't force myself to enjoy the direction this band are going in - it's simply not what I enjoy about Arcade Fire. To a lot of fans like myself, Funeral, Neon Bible and Suburbs seemed to fit together quite nicely. For me, a large chunk of reflektor felt uncomfortable to listen to. I didn't enjoy them as much. The disco/dancy/synthy stuff isn't what gravitated me towards the band. You can call that sad, say we're grovelling or say what you like. I loved this band. I still do. I love three albums of theirs - they're 3 of my favourite even. I'm very grateful the band were able to make such great music for a sustained time. \n\nOf course I expect bands to change. But it's even more short sighted to expect to like everything a band does. Eventually they'll tread waters you're not comfortable with. It doesn't mean they suddenly suck. It just means your interest and theirs are no longer aligned. But that's OK - I still have funeral, neon bible and suburbs to listen to. Any of you enjoying this new direction, have fun! Enjoy it - don't let nay sayers stop you from enjoying something. But don't dismiss people's dislike for it as not warranted neither. People have their reasons. it's taste - expecting us all to agree is fucking stupid.

author: Mark Lewis
text: What? Opinion is subjective, people like it because they like the songs (or people hate it). There has been a fair balance of people liking their stuff and people hating their stuff, that's the way it's more or less always been with AF. It might be something of a sideways step from Reflektor (IMO), but I've still enjoyed the songs more or less. This one and Signs Of Life have had less of an impact on me than the first two releases, but I've never enjoyed every song on their albums, there's always songs I can take or leave, and a handful I just don't enjoy at all. Such is the diversity of their records. \n\nWe may aswell say the people hating on it, hate electronic music, or want them to release another Funeral (which would be as retro, and regressive). I'm sure that's not really the case, but it's as equally lazy an assumption as saying the people who like this are "fanboys".

author: Jamie Adair
text: Arcade Fire wouldn't be around still if they just kept making Funeral again and again. Neon Bible is the best album, it's the one that people will look back on in a few decades and realise it was so thematically topical for the year it was released, and also so sonically different to everything else at the time. Everything Now has the weight in themes again, but it doesn't sound particularly unlike other stuff out there - they're still great songs, just let go of Wake Up, embrace change and be thankful an artist that penetrated the mainstream over a decade ago (that isn't hip hop) is still making music with some actual depth and meaning.

author: Magical Hamster
text: Goes to show how different opinions can range. I've found Neon Bible to be unbearably dour without the kind of relief you get from humor or warmth on other albums. Easily their weakest, and a poor follow up to Funeral.

author: James-Alexander Adair
text: Magical Hamster Absolutely, the nuance of taste never ceases to amaze me. There's still moments of big relief in Neon Bible though, Keep The Car Running sounds like a road trip Springsteen tune, and the horns at the end of Ocean of Noise has much more elation than most of Funeral for me. Funeral feels like a whimsical protest record, don't get me wrong I love that record to death, but Neon Bible just has that sad, cinematic beauty to it that makes it so unique, and it stands as a brilliant reflection of America at this point in history, yet it was written 10 years ago. Genius. Give it another spin with the current political backdrop and I think you'll find a new love for it!

author: gacha cookie :3
text: The average rock fan often dislikes his/her favorite band going in a more electronic and danceable direction. 'Hot Space' from Queen, or U2's 'Zooropa' are fun albums with some great songs on it, but a lot of their fans will call it their least favorite albums. I'm sure that plenty of fans didn't appreciate the Stones adding disco influences to 'Some Girls', or Radiohead leaving their guitars at home, when they recorded 'Kid A'. My favorite band of all times is Midnight Oil, and even I was not too crazy about their electronic sound on 'Redneck Wonderland'. Still, I agree with Ruth that bands have to evolve, and that the most exciting bands are bands that change their sound drastically every few albums. That's why the Beatles deserve their legendary status. In their short existence, they went through every genre known to mankind, until that moment.

author: gacha cookie :3
text: I'm not sure if I would call Arcade Fire the best band of this century, so far. It's hard to beat Radiohead's discography. But Radiohead has drifted far away from catchy pop music. They're music is best enjoyed in solitude with the lights off and no distractions. You can listen to the Arcade Fire songs, all day, every day. It's great music to wake up to, to play while working (out), to listen to on your headphones, to sing along with while cleaning the house, to play in your car, or to dance to at parties. It's a serious band, but their music is always fun to listen to.

author: gacha cookie :3
text: Arcade Fire is much more energetic for sure. I saw them in a small venue, in early 2005, months after the release of their debut album. No distance between the audience and the band. They were standing right in front of me. The band and their equipment hardly fit the stage. During most concerts, people mainly focus on the lead singer. During the Arcade Fire show, I wouldn't know where to look, because every band member was madly abusing their instrument as if he/she wanted to demolish it, and singing so loud that you would think that their  red sweaty heads were about to explode. And after every song, band members would switch instruments, and that was not something I had seen happen before. It was one of the most memorable shows in my life, for sure.

author: JofaFilms
text: I'm really loving everything off the new album so far. I understand why people might be put off by it. To me, through the marketing of the album and the disco nature of a lot of the songs I feel that they've made sort of a concept album here and they're mostly just having fun. I'm enjoying the hell out of it as these sounds sooth my soul. I think back to the reaction many people had to last year's M83 album (Junk), myself included. That album really grew on me though and while it had it's misses I find it's a bit under appreciated. I'm not put off by this new Arcade Fire though. For me it sounds like a lovely addition to their discography, even if it doesn't reach the heights of the Suburbs.

author: A l e x a n d e r
text: So we finally come to the end with another upbeat, rhythmic, synthpop, electronic, bullshit record. This is just a rehashing of the mostly uninspiring Reflektor sound with the lyrical and songwriting mediocrity of The Suburbs. They've run out of ideas and are rerunning themselves into a rapid cliched decline. So what happened to the Arcade Fire we knew? Where is the innovative and progressive indie/alt rock sound with the stings, horns and accordion etc? What happened to the dark, brooding, emotive, cathartic sound? Where is the mystery and intrigue? The band that produced "pure gold" as you say are done and dusted. This is not a "new way" of doing Arcade Fire. This is just another band which happens to have the same name and same band members.

I guess they really did do everything and gave us everything and so they've run out of ideas now.

author: Cai Revell
text: I find it rather repetitive, lacking in depth or subtlety. The titular 'Creature Comfort' aside, there's only one other bit of figurative language, which would be the the "diamond mine". Songs from all their other albums (apart from perhaps My Body Is A Cage from Neon Bible) were fun to read into and interpret, whereas Creature Comfort is boringly forward. Sure it makes a deliberate point of it, but it just doesn't do it for me. Obviously fair enough if people like it, just different flavours of Arcade Fire I suppose.

text: I think you fail to see the point that this is an album written for our current times, whereas most of the older ones were written more in a melancholic or idealistic way. I feel like they are trying to portray this modern or current feeling with sounds that represent them as well

author: Chris Conklin
text: Not comparing this to anything they have done before makes it worse. It's bland.  If you heard this in isolation without knowing who it was you would probably hate it. In a post ironic world, wrapping an album  around an ironic marketing plan is teenage thinking, and unimaginative and boring. This latest track is like second rate late era Goldfrappe, but not as good. An that itself is not good either. I cancelled my album order today. Whoever decided to release these four singles before the album should be fired.

text: The mixing of her voice is strange and almost harsh through headphones,right at the front of the mix, but the song has a great melody and some really nice harmonies. Not sure how I feel overall about the production style of some of the new collaborators. It's uncharted territory for the band and might take some getting used to. It's really heavy in the low end, almost dubby, and its very crowded sonically, which is so new for them. But overall I think its interesting for them to explore this modern 'Daft Punk' style production, so I'll keep an open mind!

The reason why I've loved AF throughout the years is the fact that they always knew how to not let their influences define them. With the new songs all I can hear now are those influences. They have proven in the past that they can do change like few other bands can but these new singles sound like something I would hear at clubs in the early 2000s. It's neither new nor fresh.
